Sophie was a hard-working editor who preferred the company of books over people. She was so diligent in her work that she barely looked up from her screen. However, she felt she needed to stay up-to-date with the latest fashion trends, so she bought a pair of oversized, emerald-green glasses. She was naive enough to think they would help her hide.

Instead, the glasses became a conversation starter. "Wow, Sophie! Those glasses look amazing on you!" her colleague barked. Sophie panicked. She knew she should say, "I appreciate that," but she just froze. "You‚Äôve got a great sense of style," another added. "Not everyone can pull off that green, but you do!"

Sophie felt exhausted. Every time she went to the water cooler, someone would say, "I love how you chose that color!" It was too much. To get rid of the constant attention, Sophie decided on a gutsy move. She took off the glasses and marched back into the office, squinting at the world.

"Finally," she thought. "No glasses, no compliments."

But the moment she sat down, her manager gasped. "Sophie! You took off those glasses! That takes guts to change your signature look so suddenly! You‚Äôre the kind of person who looks confident no matter what. You look great in your natural state too!"

Sophie sighed, realizing she couldn't win. Whether she wore the accessory or not, people were determined to notice her.
